{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c4355e3b-e03e-4cec-be3a-0fd235b9b9d9","content":"In .NET MAUI, you use the **lifecycle events API** on the `MauiAppBuilder` to map platform callbacks to cross-platform hooks.\n\nIn your `MauiProgram.cs`:\n\n```csharp\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android\n        .OnPause(activity =>\n        {\n            // runs on Android OnPause\n        })\n        .OnStop(activity =>\n        {\n            // runs on Android OnStop\n        }));\n#endif\n\n#if IOS\n    events.AddiOS(ios => ios\n        .DidEnterBackground(app =>\n        {\n            // runs on iOS DidEnterBackground\n        }));\n#endif\n});\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- Add `using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;` at the top.\n- Platform blocks are guarded with `#if ANDROID` / `#if IOS` preprocessor directives so they only compile on the target platform.\n- The handlers give you the native object (`Activity` on Android, `UIApplication` on iOS) if you need it.\n- You can also listen to `OnResume`, `OnRestart`, `WillEnterForeground`, etc. using the same pattern.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a6103146-b278-4e68-8a10-3f80199f51ce","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to hook into platform-specific lifecycle events in .NET MAUI. This is a general knowledge question about .NET MAUI development. I can answer this directly without needing to search any codebase.","outputTokens":372,"requestId":"77EF:1AA32E:7FB34FB:8DE1B05:69EABE39"},"id":"0aa39e53-4f4c-46d4-901f-9db9918a4a30","timestamp":"2026-04-24T00:50:09.773Z","parentId":"e313fb55-9e00-45b2-98f9-a4fa4821aaef"}
